it’s our 70th show. And the 110th anniversary of Mary Phagan’s death. I’ve learned many things but here are 3. During bows every night, the Star of David hanging on my chest wacks me in the face when I fold in half and it feels like a nice metaphor. secondly, I am in awe of my whole company. It’s so completely uncasual what we do and yet they make it look quite easy. my performance would be nowhere without them. And lastly, sometimes I’m pitchy and sometimes I forget lines but I don’t have to make up reasons for why that happens. It all goes better when I just leave it to the ghosts in our theater to decide why I can’t remember the name of the drug store in Atlanta. (I said it was Jordan’s drug store today. It’s Jacob’s. It’s Jacob’s drug store.)

Sky smith wrote an opinion piece with me and it was published in the New York Times today. On a red couch in Chapaqqua, NY, we decided to write about all of the discussions and debates we had exchanged over the last several months. These conversations included but were surely not limited to: why people have a hard time admitting antisemitism is racism,  the massive effect “Parade” had on both of us,  and the way my identity as a Jew has changed since playing Lucille. 

As Tom Stoppard says, “Writers aren’t sacred, but words are. If you get the right ones in the right order, you can nudge the world a little.” Sky, I think you are sacred actually. You and your words. Thank you for them. And for nudging my world in the most thoughtful and beautiful ways. 

love to our helpers, our readers, our inspirations - the smartest queerest  Jews in New York - Adam Eli (@adameli), Dana Aliya Levinson (@danaaliyalevinson), Chelsea Nachman (@chelseanachman). And thank you to the editors at the times for shockingly loving our piece so much. 

Published today. In print Sunday. Link in bio!!!!!
